            "class_4_2_2": {
              "title": "Pipeline Best Practices",
              "description": "Organizing and optimizing pipelines",
              "content_type": "text",
              "duration": 420,
              "order": 2,
              "text_content": "## Jenkins Pipeline Best Practices\n\n### 1. Use Declarative Pipeline Syntax\nDeclarative pipelines are easier to read and maintain:\n```groovy\npipeline {\n    agent any\n    stages {\n        stage('Build') {\n            steps {\n                sh 'make build'\n            }\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### 2. Store Pipelines in Source Control\n- Use Jenkinsfile in your repository\n- Version control your pipeline code\n- Enable code review for pipeline changes\n\n### 3. Use Shared Libraries\n- Reuse common pipeline code\n- Reduce duplication across projects\n- Maintain consistency\n\n### 4. Implement Proper Error Handling\n```groovy\ntry {\n    // build steps\n} catch (Exception e) {\n    // handle errors\n} finally {\n    // cleanup\n}\n```\n\n### 5. Use Parameters and Environment Variables\n- Make pipelines configurable\n- Avoid hardcoding values\n- Support multiple environments\n\n### 6. Implement Notifications\n- Email on build failures\n- Slack integration\n- Status badges\n\n### 7. Optimize Build Times\n- Use parallel stages\n- Implement caching\n- Clean workspace selectively"
            }
